---
import ArticleLayout from "../../../components/content/ArticleLayout.astro";
import ArticleHeader from "../../../components/content/ArticleHeader.astro";
import Callout from "../../../components/content/Callout.astro";
import StepsNav from "../../../components/content/StepsNav.astro";
import Step from "../../../components/content/Step.astro";
import Figure from "../../../components/content/Figure.astro";
import FigureGrid from "../../../components/content/FigureGrid.astro";
import Tip from "../../../components/content/Tip.astro";
import WrapUpCta from "../../../components/content/WrapUpCta.astro";
import installAppImg from "../../../assets/images/how-to/present-on-tv/install-app.png";
import loginQrImg from "../../../assets/images/how-to/present-on-tv/login-qr.png";
import createScreenEmptyImg from "../../../assets/images/how-to/present-on-tv/create-screen-empty.png";
import newScreenDialogImg from "../../../assets/images/how-to/present-on-tv/new-screen-dialog.png";
import selectScreenImg from "../../../assets/images/how-to/present-on-tv/select-screen.png";
import presentDropdownImg from "../../../assets/images/how-to/present-on-tv/present-dropdown.png";
import tvIdleImg from "../../../assets/images/how-to/present-on-tv/tv-idle.png";
import screenControlImg from "../../../assets/images/how-to/present-on-tv/screen-control.png";

const steps = [
  { id: "get-tv-stick", label: "Get a compatible TV stick" },
  { id: "install-app", label: "Install the TheOpenPresenter app" },
  { id: "login-qr", label: "Scan the QR code to log in" },
  { id: "select-screen", label: "Select or create a screen" },
  { id: "present", label: "Present to your TV" },
  { id: "manage", label: "Unassign when you're done" },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="How to use a TV stick to present"
  description="Run TheOpenPresenter from a TV stick instead of a laptop: get a compatible Fire TV, Google TV or Android TV device, install the app, scan a QR code to log in, assign a screen, and present from your project."
>
  <ArticleHeader
    backHref="/how-to"
    backLabel="All how-to guides"
    category="For churches"
    minutes={5}
    title="How to use a TV stick to present"
  >
    No laptop, no cables, no fuss. With a small TV stick plugged into
    your screen, TheOpenPresenter runs straight on the TV. For small
    gatherings, whoever is leading just brings the stick, plugs it in,
    and controls everything from their phone or computer.
  </ArticleHeader>

  <Callout>
    This guide assumes you already have an organization and a project set up.
    If you don't yet, follow our{" "}
    <a
      href="/how-to/use-online-for-church"
      class="text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400 hover:underline font-medium"
      >guide on using the online version for church</a
    >{" "}
    first. You'll also need a TV or projector with a spare HDMI port and Wi-Fi
    in the room.
  </Callout>

  <StepsNav steps={steps} />

  <Step id="get-tv-stick" number={1} title="Get a compatible TV stick">
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      A TV stick is a small device that plugs into your TV's HDMI port and
      turns any screen into a smart TV. TheOpenPresenter runs as an app on
      the stick, so this is all you need to carry to your gathering. Any of
      the following will work:
    </p>

    <ul
      class="list-disc list-outside pl-5 space-y-2 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6"
    >
      <li>
        <strong class="font-semibold">Amazon Fire TV</strong> (Fire TV
        Stick)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong class="font-semibold">Google TV</strong> (such as the
        Chromecast with Google TV)
      </li>
      <li><strong class="font-semibold">Android TV</strong> devices</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      Check the up-to-date list of supported devices on our{" "}
      <a
        href="https://theopenpresenter.com/download/"
        class="text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400 hover:underline font-medium"
        >download page</a
      >. We're adding more platforms (like Samsung TVs) over time, so it's
      worth a look before you buy.
    </p>

    <Tip>
      Set the stick up once at home, connect it to your church's Wi-Fi, and
      it's ready to go. On the day, you only need to plug it in and switch the
      TV to the right HDMI input.
    </Tip>
  </Step>

  <Step id="install-app" number={2} title="Install the TheOpenPresenter app">
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      On the TV stick, open its app store and search for{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">TheOpenPresenter</strong>.
    </p>

    <ol
      class="list-decimal list-outside pl-5 space-y-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6"
    >
      <li>
        Open the app store on your device (the{" "}
        <strong class="font-semibold">Amazon Appstore</strong> on Fire TV,
        or <strong class="font-semibold">Google Play</strong> on Google TV
        and Android TV).
      </li>
      <li>
        Search for{" "}
        <strong class="font-semibold">TheOpenPresenter</strong> and select
        it.
      </li>
      <li>
        Choose <strong class="font-semibold">Get App</strong> (or{" "}
        <strong class="font-semibold">Install</strong>), then open it. The
        app is free to download.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <Figure
      src={installAppImg}
      alt="The TheOpenPresenter app listing on the Amazon Appstore, showing it is free to download with a Get App button"
      size="xl"
      class="mb-6"
    />

    <Tip>
      Can't find the app on your device? Double-check that your device is on
      our{" "}
      <a
        href="https://theopenpresenter.com/download/"
        class="text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400 hover:underline font-medium"
        >download page</a
      >, which always links to the right store for each platform.
    </Tip>
  </Step>

  <Step id="login-qr" number={3} title="Scan the QR code to log in">
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      Typing an email and password with a TV remote is painful, so the app
      lets you log in by scanning a QR code instead. When you open the app,
      the <strong class="font-semibold">Set up this device</strong> screen
      shows a QR code on the TV.
    </p>

    <ol
      class="list-decimal list-outside pl-5 space-y-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6"
    >
      <li>Open the camera app on your phone.</li>
      <li>
        Point it at the QR code on the TV and tap the link that appears.
      </li>
      <li>
        Sign in with the same TheOpenPresenter account you use on your
        computer, then confirm to link the device.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      The TV shows <em>Waiting for sign-in…</em> and signs in
      automatically the moment you finish on your phone.
    </p>

    <Figure
      src={loginQrImg}
      alt="The Set up this device screen on the TV, with a QR code to scan and three steps: open your camera, point it at the code, sign in and link your account"
      size="2xl"
      class="mb-6"
    />

    <Tip>
      You only have to do this once per device. The TV stays logged in for
      next time.
    </Tip>
  </Step>

  <Step id="select-screen" number={4} title="Select or create a screen">
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      A <strong class="font-semibold">screen</strong> is TheOpenPresenter's
      name for an output display. Assigning this TV to a screen is what lets
      you send your slides to it later. After logging in, the{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">Connect this TV</strong> screen asks you
      to create or pick a screen from your organization.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">
      If you don't have a screen yet
    </p>
    <ol
      class="list-decimal list-outside pl-5 space-y-3 text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6"
    >
      <li>
        You'll see <strong class="font-semibold">No screens yet</strong>.
        Click <strong class="font-semibold">Create screen</strong>.
      </li>
      <li>
        In the <strong class="font-semibold">New Screen</strong> window,
        give it a clear <strong class="font-semibold">Name</strong>, for
        example <em>Main Screen</em> or <em>Meeting room</em>. You can
        leave <strong class="font-semibold">Slug</strong> blank, it's
        filled in from the name.
      </li>
      <li>Click <strong class="font-semibold">Create</strong>.</li>
    </ol>

    <FigureGrid cols={2}>
      <Figure
        src={createScreenEmptyImg}
        alt="The Connect this TV screen showing No screens yet, with a red arrow pointing at the Create screen button"
      />
      <Figure
        src={newScreenDialogImg}
        alt="The New Screen window with a Name field set to Main Screen, an optional Slug field, and a Create button"
      />
    </FigureGrid>

    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">
      If you already have a screen
    </p>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      Pick it from the list under your organization and tap it to assign
      this TV to it. You can also choose{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">Create new screen</strong> to add
      another one.
    </p>

    <Figure
      src={selectScreenImg}
      alt="The Connect this TV screen listing an existing screen called Main Screen under the organization, with a red arrow pointing at it to select it"
      size="lg"
      class="mb-6"
    />

    <Tip>
      Give each screen a name that matches where it lives in the room. If you
      add a second TV later, clear names make it obvious which output you're
      sending to.
    </Tip>

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mt-6 mb-4">
      Once you assign the screen, your phone opens the{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">Screen Control</strong> panel for it,
      ready for you to open a project. The TV is now connected and waiting
      for input.
    </p>

    <Figure
      src={screenControlImg}
      alt="The Screen Control panel for Meeting room on a phone, with an Open a project list and a New button to create a project"
      size="lg"
    />
  </Step>

  <Step id="present" number={5} title="Present to your TV">
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      With the TV assigned to a screen, there are two easy ways to get your
      slides onto it.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">
      From the screen's control panel
    </p>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      This is the panel you land on right after assigning the screen in
      step 4. Under <strong class="font-semibold">Open a project</strong>,
      pick an existing project or use{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">New</strong> to start one. It appears on
      the TV straight away, and you control the slides from your phone.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-3">
      From a project you already have open
    </p>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      On your computer or phone, open the project and click{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">Present</strong>. Under{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">Present to a screen</strong>, choose the
      screen you assigned to this TV (for example{" "}
      <em>Meeting room</em>). Your slides appear on the TV straight away.
    </p>

    <Figure
      src={presentDropdownImg}
      alt="The Present menu in the editor showing Open in new tab and, under Present to a screen, a screen called Meeting room marked Idle, with a red arrow pointing at it"
      size="sm"
      center={false}
      class="mb-8"
    />

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      <strong class="font-semibold">Need the control panel again later?</strong>{" "}
      While nothing is being presented, the TV shows an{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">Awaiting input</strong> screen with a QR
      code. Scan it (or go to{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">theopenpresenter.com/connect</strong> and
      enter the code shown on the TV) to reopen that screen's control panel
      on any phone, no computer needed.
    </p>

    <Figure
      src={tvIdleImg}
      alt="The idle TV screen titled Main Screen, Awaiting input, with a Scan to control QR code, the URL theopenpresenter.com/connect, and a short code"
      size="2xl"
      class="mb-6"
    />

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">
      Want to run everything from your phone? See our{" "}
      <a
        href="/how-to/control-with-phone"
        class="text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400 hover:underline font-medium"
        >guide on controlling from your phone</a
      >.
    </p>
  </Step>

  <Step id="manage" number={6} title="Unassign when you're done">
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">
      When the service is over, you can tidy up without touching the TV or
      its remote.
    </p>

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-6">
      <strong class="font-semibold">Unassign the project</strong> to
      disconnect it from the screen, freeing the TV up for the next project
      or the next gathering. The TV goes back to its{" "}
      <em>Awaiting input</em> screen. You can unassign from the{" "}
      <strong class="font-semibold">Screen Control</strong> panel, or
      straight from the project you were presenting.
    </p>

    <Tip class="mb-6">
      Don't want to remember this every week? Open the screen's settings and
      turn on <strong class="font-semibold">auto-unassign</strong>, and the
      screen frees itself automatically once you're done.
    </Tip>

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">
      That's it. Next time, just plug the stick in, present to the same
      screen, and you're live again.
    </p>
  </Step>

  <WrapUpCta
    title="Just bring the stick"
    buttons={[
      {
        label: "See supported devices",
        href: "https://theopenpresenter.com/download/",
        variant: "primary",
      },
      {
        label: "Read the full guide",
        href: "/how-to/use-online-for-church",
        variant: "secondary",
      },
    ]}
  >
    A TV stick, your church Wi-Fi, and a phone in your pocket is all it
    takes to run a gathering, no laptop required. New to
    TheOpenPresenter? Start with the full walkthrough.
  </WrapUpCta>
</ArticleLayout>
